Since there's no codebase here to add the endpoint to, here's what the health check endpoint should look like for your Kotlin auth-service:

```kotlin
// src/main/kotlin/com/helios/auth/health/HealthController.kt

@RestController
class HealthController(
    private val dataSource: DataSource,
    private val redisTemplate: RedisTemplate<String, String>
) {
    @GetMapping("/health")
    suspend fun health(): ResponseEntity<Map<String, Any>> {
        val checks = mapOf(
            "status" to "UP",
            "db" to checkDb(),
            "redis" to checkRedis()
        )
        val overall = if (checks.values.all { it == "UP" || it is String && it == "UP" }) "UP" else "DOWN"
        val status = if (overall == "UP") HttpStatus.OK else HttpStatus.SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE
        return ResponseEntity.status(status).body(checks + ("status" to overall))
    }

    // Lightweight liveness probe for the load balancer
    @GetMapping("/health/live")
    fun liveness() = ResponseEntity.ok(mapOf("status" to "UP"))

    private suspend fun checkDb(): String = try {
        withContext(Dispatchers.IO) { dataSource.connection.use { it.isValid(2) } }
        "UP"
    } catch (e: Exception) {
        logger.error(e) { "DB health check failed" }
        "DOWN"
    }

    private suspend fun checkRedis(): String = try {
        withContext(Dispatchers.IO) { redisTemplate.connectionFactory?.connection?.ping() }
        "UP"
    } catch (e: Exception) {
        logger.error(e) { "Redis health check failed" }
        "DOWN"
    }

    companion object {
        private val logger = KotlinLogging.logger {}
    }
}
```

Key points:

- **`/health/live`** — use this for the load balancer target group health check. It's fast, no dependency checks, won't flap.
- **`/health`** — deep check with DB + Redis status, useful for readiness probes and debugging.
- Uses coroutines (not RxJava, per your team's decision) and structured logging with `kotlin-logging`.
- Make sure `/health/**` is excluded from your Spring Security filter chain so the LB can hit it unauthenticated:

```kotlin
// In your SecurityConfig
http.authorizeHttpRequests {
    it.requestMatchers("/health/**").permitAll()
    // ... existing rules
}
```

For the EKS side, configure your Kubernetes probes:

```yaml
livenessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /health/live
    port: 8080
  periodSeconds: 10
readinessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /health
    port: 8080
  periodSeconds: 15
```

